#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:9
#, no-c-format
msgid "Building Profiles from the Command Line"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:16
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aareg; provides the user the ability to use a command line interface rather than a graphical interface to manage and configure the system security. Track the status of &aa; and create, delete, or modify &aa; profiles using the &aa; command line tools."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:23
#, no-c-format
msgid "Background Information"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:24
#, no-c-format
msgid "Before starting to manage your profiles using the &aa; command line tools, check out the general introduction to &aa; given in <xref linkend=\"cha.apparmor.concept\"/> and <xref linkend=\"cha.apparmor.profiles\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:32
#, no-c-format
msgid "Checking the &aa; Status"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aa; can be in any one of three states:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:40
#, no-c-format
msgid "Unloaded"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:42
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aa; is not activated in the kernel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:48
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:50
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aa; is activated in the kernel and is enforcing &aa; program policies."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:57
#, no-c-format
msgid "Stopped"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:59
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aa; is activated in the kernel, but no policies are enforced."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Detect the state of &aa; by inspecting <filename>/sys/kernel/security/apparmor/profiles</filename> . If <command>cat /sys/kernel/security/apparmor/profiles</command> reports a list of profiles, &aa; is running. If it is empty and returns nothing, &aa; is stopped. If the file does not exist, &aa; is unloaded."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:74
#, no-c-format
msgid "Manage &aa; with <command>systemctl</command> . It lets you perform the following operations:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:81
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>sudo systemctl start apparmor</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:84
#, no-c-format
msgid "Behavior depends on the state of &aa;. If it is not activated, <option>start</option> activates and starts it, putting it in the running state. If it is stopped, <option>start</option> causes the re-scan of &aa; profiles usually found in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> and puts &aa; in the running state. If &aa; is already running, <option>start</option> reports a warning and takes no action."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:94
#, no-c-format
msgid "Already Running Processes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid "Already running processes need to be restarted to apply the &aa; profiles on them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:103
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>sudo systemctl stop apparmor</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:106
#, no-c-format
msgid "Stops &aa; if it is running by removing all profiles from kernel memory, effectively disabling all access controls, and putting &aa; into the stopped state. If the &aa; is already stopped, <option>stop</option> tries to unload the profiles again, but nothing happens."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:116
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>sudo systemctl reload apparmor</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:119
#, no-c-format
msgid "Causes the &aa; module to re-scan the profiles in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> without unconfining running <remark>sknorr, 2014-08-26: \"unconfining\"? Sounds terrible. Would \"freeing\" be an option? tbazant, 2014-09-08: No, it's a used term, related to 'unconfined' state </remark> processes. Freshly created profiles are enforced and recently deleted ones are removed from the <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:135
#, no-c-format
msgid "Building &aa; Profiles"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:137
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &aa; module profile definitions are stored in the <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> directory as plain text files. For a detailed description of the syntax of these files, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.apparmor.profiles\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid "All files in the <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> directory are interpreted as profiles and are loaded as such. Renaming files in that directory is not an effective way of preventing profiles from being loaded. You must remove profiles from this directory to prevent them from being read and evaluated effectively, or call <command>aa-disable</command> on the profile, which will create a symbolic link in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d/disabled/</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:154
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can use a text editor, such as <command>vi</command> , to access and make changes to these profiles. The following sections contain detailed steps for building profiles:"
msgstr ""

