#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:304
#, no-c-format
msgid "Two Methods of Profiling"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:306
#, no-c-format
msgid "Given the syntax for &aa; profiles in <xref xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\" linkend=\"cha.apparmor.profiles\"/> , you could create profiles without using the tools. However, the effort involved would be substantial. To avoid such a situation, use the &aa; tools to automate the creation and refinement of profiles."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:314
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are two ways to approach &aa; profile creation. Tools are available for both methods."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid "A method suitable for profiling small applications that have a finite runtime, such as user client applications like mail clients. For more information, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.stand-alone\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid "A method suitable for profiling many programs at once and for profiling applications that may run for days, weeks, or continuously across reboots, such as network server applications like Web servers and mail servers. For more information, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.systemic\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:345
#, no-c-format
msgid "Automated profile development becomes more manageable with the &aa; tools:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:352
#, no-c-format
msgid "Decide which profiling method suits your needs."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:357
#, no-c-format
msgid "Perform a static analysis. Run either <command>aa-genprof</command> or <command>aa-autodep</command> , depending on the profiling method chosen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable dynamic learning. Activate learning mode for all profiled programs."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid "Stand-Alone Profiling"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:373
#, no-c-format
msgid "Stand-alone profile generation and improvement is managed by a program called <command>aa-genprof</command> . This method is easy because <command>aa-genprof</command> takes care of everything, but is limited because it requires <command>aa-genprof</command> to run for the entire duration of the test run of your program (you cannot reboot the machine while you are still developing your profile)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:381
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use <command>aa-genprof</command> for the stand-alone method of profiling, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:389
#, no-c-format
msgid "Systemic Profiling"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "This method is called <emphasis>systemic profiling</emphasis> because it updates all of the profiles on the system at once, rather than focusing on the one or few targeted by <command>aa-genprof</command> or stand-alone profiling. With systemic profiling, profile construction and improvement are somewhat less automated, but more flexible. This method is suitable for profiling long-running applications whose behavior continues after rebooting, or many programs at once."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:399
#, no-c-format
msgid "Build an &aa; profile for a group of applications as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create profiles for the individual programs that make up your application."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:408
#, no-c-format
msgid "Although this approach is systemic, &aa; only monitors those programs with profiles and their children. To get &aa; to consider a program, you must at least have <command>aa-autodep</command> create an approximate profile for it. To create this approximate profile, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.autodep\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:418
#, no-c-format
msgid "Put relevant profiles into learning or complain mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:421
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activate learning or complain mode for all profiled programs by entering"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-complain /etc/apparmor.d/*"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:426
#, no-c-format
msgid "in a terminal window while logged in as &rootuser;. This functionality is also available through the &yast; Profile Mode module, described in <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.yast.manage.profmodes\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:432
#, no-c-format
msgid "When in learning mode, access requests are not blocked, even if the profile dictates that they should be. This enables you to run through several tests (as shown in <xref linkend=\"st.apparmor.commandline.profiling.systemic.exec\"/> ) and learn the access needs of the program so it runs properly. With this information, you can decide how secure to make the profile."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.complain\"/> for more detailed instructions for using learning or complain mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:447
#, no-c-format
msgid "Exercise your application."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:450
#, no-c-format
msgid "Run your application and exercise its functionality. How much to exercise the program is up to you, but you need the program to access each file representing its access needs. Because the execution is not being supervised by <command>aa-genprof</command> , this step can go on for days or weeks and can span complete system reboots."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:459
#, no-c-format
msgid "Analyze the log."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:462
#, no-c-format
msgid "In systemic profiling, run <command>aa-logprof</command> directly instead of letting <command>aa-genprof</command> run it (as in stand-alone profiling). The general form of <command>aa-logprof</command> is:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:468
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-logprof [ -d <replaceable>/path/to/profiles</replaceable> ] [ -f <replaceable>/path/to/logfile</replaceable> ]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:469
#, no-c-format
msgid "Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.logprof\"/> for more information about using <command>aa-logprof</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:476
#, no-c-format
msgid "Repeat <xref linkend=\"st.apparmor.commandline.profiling.systemic.exec\"/> and <xref linkend=\"st.apparmor.commandline.profiling.systemic.log\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:481
#, no-c-format
msgid "This generates optimal profiles. An iterative approach captures smaller data sets that can be trained and reloaded into the policy engine. Subsequent iterations generate fewer messages and run faster."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:488
#, no-c-format
msgid "Edit the profiles."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:491
#, no-c-format
msgid "You should review the profiles that have been generated. You can open and edit the profiles in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d/</filename> using a text editor."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:498
#, no-c-format
msgid "Return to enforce mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is when the system goes back to enforcing the rules of the profiles, not only logging information. This can be done manually by removing the <literal>flags=(complain)</literal> text from the <!-- could also be a symbolic link in /etc/apparmor.d/force-complain/ --> profiles or automatically by using the <command>aa-enforce</command> command, which works identically to the <command>aa-complain</command> command, except it sets the profiles to enforce mode. This functionality is also available through the &yast; Profile Mode module, described in <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.yast.manage.profmodes\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid "To ensure that all profiles are taken out of complain mode and put into enforce mode, enter <command>aa-enforce /etc/apparmor.d/*</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:520
#, no-c-format
msgid "Re-scan all profiles."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:523
#, no-c-format
msgid "To have &aa; re-scan all of the profiles and change the enforcement mode in the kernel, enter <command>systemctl reload apparmor</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:533
#, no-c-format
msgid "Summary of Profiling Tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:534
#, no-c-format
msgid "All of the &aa; profiling utilities are provided by the <systemitem>apparmor-utils</systemitem> RPM package and are stored in <filename>/usr/sbin</filename> . Each tool has a different purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:540
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-autodep&mdash;Creating Approximate Profiles"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:541
#, no-c-format
msgid "This creates an approximate profile for the program or application selected. You can generate approximate profiles for binary executables and interpreted script programs. The resulting profile is called <quote>approximate</quote> because it does not necessarily contain all of the profile entries that the program needs to be properly confined by &aa;. The minimum <command>aa-autodep</command> approximate profile has, at minimum, a base include directive, which contains basic profile entries needed by most programs. For certain types of programs, <command>aa-autodep</command> generates a more expanded profile. The profile is generated by recursively calling <command>ldd(1)</command> on the executables listed on the command line."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:554
#, no-c-format
msgid "To generate an approximate profile, use the <command>aa-autodep</command> program. The program argument can be either the simple name of the program, which <command>aa-autodep</command> finds by searching your shell's path variable, or it can be a fully qualified path. The program itself can be of any type (ELF binary, shell script, Perl script, etc.). <command>aa-autodep</command> generates an approximate profile to improve through the dynamic profiling that follows."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:564
#, no-c-format
msgid "The resulting approximate profile is written to the <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> directory using the &aa; profile naming convention of naming the profile after the absolute path of the program, replacing the forward slash ( <literal>/</literal> ) characters in the path with period ( <literal>.</literal> ) characters. The general syntax of <command>aa-autodep</command> is to enter the following in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:573
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-autodep [ -d <replaceable>/PATH/TO/PROFILES</replaceable> ] [<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable> <replaceable>PROGRAM2</replaceable>...]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:574
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you do not enter the program name or names, you are prompted for them. <replaceable>/path/to/profiles</replaceable> overrides the default location of <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> , should you keep profiles in a location other than the default."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:580
#, no-c-format
msgid "To begin profiling, you must create profiles for each main executable service that is part of your application (anything that might start without being a child of another program that already has a profile). Finding all such programs depends on the application in question. Here are several strategies for finding such programs:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:589
#, no-c-format
msgid "Directories"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:591
#, no-c-format
msgid "If all the programs to profile are in one directory and there are no other programs in that directory, the simple command <command>aa-autodep</command> <replaceable>/path/to/your/programs/*</replaceable> creates basic profiles for all programs in that directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:601
#, no-c-format
msgid "pstree -p"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can run your application and use the standard Linux <command>pstree</command> command to find all processes running. Then manually hunt down the location of these programs and run the <command>aa-autodep</command> for each one. If the programs are in your path, <command>aa-autodep</command> finds them for you. If they are not in your path, the standard Linux command <command>find</command> might be helpful in finding your programs. Execute <command>find / -name '</command> <replaceable>MY_APPLICATION</replaceable> ' -print to determine an application's path ( <replaceable>MY_APPLICATION</replaceable> being an example application). You may use wild cards if appropriate."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:621
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-complain&mdash;Entering Complain or Learning Mode"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:622
#, no-c-format
msgid "The complain or learning mode tool ( <command>aa-complain</command> ) detects violations of &aa; profile rules, such as the profiled program accessing files not permitted by the profile. The violations are permitted, but also logged. To improve the profile, turn complain mode on, run the program through a suite of tests to generate log events that characterize the program's access needs, then postprocess the log with the &aa; tools to transform log events into improved profiles."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:632
#, no-c-format
msgid "Manually activating complain mode (using the command line) adds a flag to the top of the profile so that <literal>/bin/foo</literal> becomes <literal>/bin/foo flags=(complain)</literal> . To use complain mode, <!-- or create a symbolic link in force-complain --> open a terminal window and enter one of the following lines as &rootuser;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:646
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-complain [<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable> <replaceable>PROGRAM2</replaceable> ...]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:649
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the program is not in your path, specify the entire path as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:653
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-complain /sbin/<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:656
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the profiles are not in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> , use the following to override the default location:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-complain <replaceable>/path/to/profiles/</replaceable><replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:667
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-complain /etc/apparmor.d/sbin.<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:670
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each of the above commands activates the complain mode for the profiles or programs listed. If the program name does not include its entire path, <command>aa-complain</command> searches <envar>$PATH</envar> for the program. For example, <command>aa-complain /usr/sbin/*</command> finds profiles associated with all of the programs in <filename>/usr/sbin</filename> and puts them into complain mode. <command>aa-complain /etc/apparmor.d/*</command> puts all of the profiles in <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> into complain mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:690
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-decode&mdash;Decoding Hex-encoded Strings in &aa; Log Files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:691
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>aa-decode</command> will decode hex-encoded strings in the &aa; log output. It can also process the audit log on standard input, convert any hex-encoded &aa; log entries, and display them on standard output."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:699
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-disable&mdash;Disabling an &aa; Security Profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:700
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use <command>aa-disable</command> to disable the enforcement mode for one or more &aa; profiles. This command will unload the profile from the kernel, and prevent the profile from being loaded on &aa; start-up. Use <command>aa-enforce</command> or <command>aa-complain</command> utilities to change this behavior."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-easyprof&mdash;Easy Profile Generation"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:710
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>aa-easyprof</command> provides an easy-to-use interface for &aa; profile generation. <command>aa-easyprof</command> supports the use of templates and profile groups to quickly profile an application. While <command>aa-easyprof</command> can help with profile generation, its utility is dependent on the quality of the templates, profile groups and abstractions used. Also, this tool may create a profile that is less restricted than when creating a profile manually or with <command>aa-genprof</command> and <command>aa-logprof</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:720
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information, see the man page of <command>aa-easyprof</command> (8)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:726
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-enforce&mdash;Entering Enforce Mode"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:727
#, no-c-format
msgid "The enforce mode detects violations of &aa; profile rules, such as the profiled program accessing files not permitted by the profile. The violations are logged and not permitted. The default is for enforce mode to be enabled. To log the violations only, but still permit them, use complain mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:734
#, no-c-format
msgid "Manually activating enforce mode (using the command line) removes the complain flag from the top of the profile so that <literal>/bin/foo flags=(complain)</literal> becomes <literal>/bin/foo</literal> . To use enforce mode, open a terminal window and enter one of the following lines."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:743
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the example program ( <replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable> ) is in your path, use:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:747
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-enforce [<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable> <replaceable>PROGRAM2</replaceable> ...]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:750
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the program is not in your path, specify the entire path, as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:754
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-enforce /sbin/<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:757
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the profiles are not in <replaceable>/etc/apparmor.d</replaceable> , use the following to override the default location:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:762
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-enforce -d <replaceable>/path/to/profiles/     program1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:765
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify the profile for <replaceable>/sbin/program1</replaceable> as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:769
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-enforce /etc/apparmor.d/sbin.<replaceable>PROGRAM1</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:772
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each of the above commands activates the enforce mode for the profiles and programs listed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:776
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you do not enter the program or profile names, you are prompted to enter one. <replaceable>/path/to/profiles</replaceable> overrides the default location of <filename>/etc/apparmor.d</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:781
#, no-c-format
msgid "The argument can be either a list of programs or a list of profiles. If the program name does not include its entire path, <command>aa-enforce</command> searches <envar>$PATH</envar> for the program."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:788
#, no-c-format
msgid "Toggling Profile Mode with &yast;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:789
#, no-c-format
msgid "&yast; offers a graphical front-end for toggling complain and enforce mode. See <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.yast.manage.profmodes\"/> for information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:797
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-exec&mdash;Confining a Program with the Specified Profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:798
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use <command>aa-exec</command> to launch a program confined by a specified profile and/or profile namespace. If both a profile and namespace are specified, the program will be confined by the profile in the new namespace. If only a profile namespace is specified, the profile name of the current confinement will be used. If neither a profile nor namespace is specified, the command will be run using the standard profile attachment&mdash;as if you did not use the <command>aa-exec</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:808
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information on the command's options, see its manual page <command>man 8 aa-exec</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:814
#, no-c-format
msgid "aa-genprof&mdash;Generating Profiles"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:815
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>aa-genprof</command> is &aa;'s profile generating utility. It runs <command>aa-autodep</command> on the specified program, creating an approximate profile (if a profile does not already exist for it), sets it to complain mode, reloads it into &aa;, marks the log, and prompts the user to execute the program and exercise its functionality. Its syntax is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:823
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;aa-genprof [ -d <replaceable>/path/to/profiles</replaceable> ]  <replaceable>PROGRAM</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:824
#, no-c-format
msgid "To create a profile for the Apache Web server program httpd2-prefork, do the following as &rootuser;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:830
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enter <command>systemctl stop apache2</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:835
#, no-c-format
msgid "Next, enter <command>aa-genprof httpd2-prefork</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:838
#, no-c-format
msgid "Now <command>aa-genprof</command> does the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:843
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resolves the full path of httpd2-prefork using your shell's path variables. You can also specify a full path. On &productname;, the default full path is <phrase><filename>/usr/sbin/httpd2-prefork</filename></phrase> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:851
#, no-c-format
msgid "Checks to see if there is an existing profile for httpd2-prefork. If there is one, it updates it. If not, it creates one using the <command>aa-autodep</command> as described in <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:859
#, no-c-format
msgid "Puts the profile for this program into learning or complain mode so that profile violations are logged, but are permitted to proceed. A log event looks like this (see <filename>/var/log/audit/audit.log</filename> ):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:865
#, no-c-format
msgid "type=APPARMOR_ALLOWED msg=audit(1189682639.184:20816): \\\n"
      "apparmor=\"DENIED\" operation=\"file_mmap\" parent=2692 \\\n"
      "profile=\"/usr/sbin/httpd2-prefork//HANDLING_UNTRUSTED_INPUT\" \\\n"
      "name=\"/var/log/apache2/access_log-20140116\" pid=28730 comm=\"httpd2-prefork\" \\\n"
      "requested_mask=\"::r\" denied_mask=\"::r\" fsuid=30 ouid=0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:870
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are not running the audit daemon, the &aa; events are logged directly to &systemd; journal (see <xref linkend=\"cha.journalctl\"/> ):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:875
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sep 13 13:20:30 K23 kernel: audit(1189682430.672:20810): \\\n"
      "apparmor=\"DENIED\" operation=\"file_mmap\" parent=2692 \\\n"
      "profile=\"/usr/sbin/httpd2-prefork//HANDLING_UNTRUSTED_INPUT\" \\\n"
      "name=\"/var/log/apache2/access_log-20140116\" pid=28730 comm=\"httpd2-prefork\" \\\n"
      "requested_mask=\"::r\" denied_mask=\"::r\" fsuid=30 ouid=0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:880
#, no-c-format
msgid "They also can be viewed using the <command>dmesg</command> command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:883
#, no-c-format
msgid "audit(1189682430.672:20810): apparmor=\"DENIED\" \\\n"
      "operation=\"file_mmap\" parent=2692 \\\n"
      "profile=\"/usr/sbin/httpd2-prefork//HANDLING_UNTRUSTED_INPUT\" \\\n"
      "name=\"/var/log/apache2/access_log-20140116\" pid=28730 comm=\"httpd2-prefork\" \\\n"
      "requested_mask=\"::r\" denied_mask=\"::r\" fsuid=30 ouid=0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:890
#, no-c-format
msgid "Marks the log with a beginning marker of log events to consider. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:894
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "Sep 13 17:48:52 figwit root: GenProf: e2ff78636296f16d0b5301209a04430d"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:900
#, no-c-format
msgid "When prompted by the tool, run the application to profile in another terminal window and perform as many of the application functions as possible. Thus, the learning mode can log the files and directories to which the program requires access to function properly. For example, in a new terminal window, enter <command>systemctl start apache2</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:910
#, no-c-format
msgid "Select from the following options that are available in the <command>aa-genprof</command> terminal window after you have executed the program function:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:917
#, no-c-format
msgid "<keycap>S</keycap> runs <command>aa-genprof</command> on the system log from where it was marked when <command>aa-genprof</command> was started and reloads the profile. If system events exist in the log, &aa; parses the learning mode log files. This generates a series of questions that you must answer to guide <command>aa-genprof</command> in generating the security profile."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:927
#, no-c-format
msgid "<keycap>F</keycap> exits the tool."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:933
#, no-c-format
msgid "If requests to add hats appear, proceed to <xref linkend=\"cha.apparmor.hat\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:940
#, no-c-format
msgid "Answer two types of questions:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:945
#, no-c-format
msgid "A resource is requested by a profiled program that is not in the profile (see <xref linkend=\"ex.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof.learn\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:952
#, no-c-format
msgid "A program is executed by the profiled program and the security domain transition has not been defined (see <xref linkend=\"ex.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof.perms\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:959
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each of these categories results in a series of questions that you must answer to add the resource or program to the profile. <xref linkend=\"ex.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof.learn\"/> and <xref linkend=\"ex.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof.perms\"/> provide examples of each one. Subsequent steps describe your options in answering these questions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:970
#, no-c-format
msgid "Dealing with execute accesses is complex. You must decide how to proceed with this entry regarding which execute permission type to grant to this entry:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:976
#, no-c-format
msgid "Learning Mode Exception: Controlling Access to Specific Resources"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:977
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reading log entries from /var/log/audit/audit.log.\n"
      "Updating AppArmor profiles in /etc/apparmor.d.\n"
      "\n"
      "Profile:  /usr/sbin/cupsd\n"
      "Program:  cupsd\n"
      "Execute:  /usr/lib/cups/daemon/cups-lpd\n"
      "Severity: unknown\n"
      "\n"
      "(I)nherit / (P)rofile / (C)hild / (N)ame / (U)nconfined / (X)ix / (D)eny / Abo(r)t / (F)inish"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:989
#, no-c-format
msgid "Inherit (ix)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:991
#, no-c-format
msgid "The child inherits the parent's profile, running with the same access controls as the parent. This mode is useful when a confined program needs to call another confined program without gaining the permissions of the target's profile or losing the permissions of the current profile. This mode is often used when the child program is a <emphasis>helper application</emphasis> , such as the <command>/usr/bin/mail</command> client using <command>less</command> as a pager."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1004
#, no-c-format
msgid "Profile (px/Px)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1006
#, no-c-format
msgid "The child runs using its own profile, which must be loaded into the kernel. If the profile is not present, attempts to execute the child fail with permission denied. This is most useful if the parent program is invoking a global service, such as DNS lookups or sending mail with your system's MTA."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1013
#, no-c-format
msgid "Choose the <guimenu>profile with clean exec</guimenu> (Px) option to scrub the environment of environment variables that could modify execution behavior when passed to the child process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1022
#, no-c-format
msgid "Child (cx/Cx)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1024
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sets up a transition to a subprofile. It is like px/Px transition, except to a child profile."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1028
#, no-c-format
msgid "Choose the <guimenu>profile with clean exec</guimenu> (Cx) option to scrub the environment of environment variables that could modify execution behavior when passed to the child process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1037
#, no-c-format
msgid "Unconfined (ux/Ux)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1039
#, no-c-format
msgid "The child runs completely unconfined without any &aa; profile applied to the executed resource."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1043
#, no-c-format
msgid "Choose the <guimenu>unconfined with clean exec</guimenu> (Ux) option to scrub the environment of environment variables that could modify execution behavior when passed to the child process. Note that running unconfined profiles introduces a security vulnerability that could be used to evade &aa;. Only use it as a last resort."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1054
#, no-c-format
msgid "mmap (m)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1056
#, no-c-format
msgid "This permission denotes that the program running under the profile can access the resource using the mmap system call with the flag <envar>PROT_EXEC</envar> . This means that the data mapped in it can be executed. You are prompted to include this permission if it is requested during a profiling run."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1068
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adds a <literal>deny</literal> rule to the profile, and permanently prevents the program from accessing the specified directory path entries. &aa; then continues to the next event."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1097
#, no-c-format
msgid "<xref linkend=\"ex.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.genprof.perms\"/> shows &aa; suggest allowing a globbing pattern <filename>/var/run/nscd/*</filename> for reading, then using an abstraction to cover common Apache-related access rules."
msgstr ""

