      "(A)llow / [(D)eny] / (G)lob / Glob w/(E)xt / (N)ew / Abo(r)t / (F)inish / (O)pts\n"
      "Adding #include &lt;abstractions/apache2-common&gt; to profile.\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1129
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aa; provides one or more paths or includes. By entering the option number, select the desired options then proceed to the next step."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1135
#, no-c-format
msgid "Not all of these options are always presented in the &aa; menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1141
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>#include</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1144
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is the section of an &aa; profile that refers to an include file, which procures access permissions for programs. By using an include, you can give the program access to directory paths or files that are also required by other programs. Using includes can reduce the size of a profile. It is good practice to select includes when suggested."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1155
#, no-c-format
msgid "Globbed Version"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1157
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is accessed by selecting <guimenu>Glob</guimenu> as described in the next step. For information about globbing syntax, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.profiles.glob\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1165
#, no-c-format
msgid "Actual Path"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1167
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is the literal path to which the program needs access so that it can run properly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1174
#, no-c-format
msgid "After you select the path or include, process it as an entry into the &aa; profile by selecting <guimenu>Allow</guimenu> or <guimenu>Deny</guimenu> . If you are not satisfied with the directory path entry as it is displayed, you can also <guimenu>Glob</guimenu> it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1181
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following options are available to process the learning mode entries and build the profile:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1190
#, no-c-format
msgid "Allows access to the selected directory path."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1198
#, no-c-format
msgid "Allows access to the specified directory path entries. &aa; suggests file permission access. For more information, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.profiles.perm\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1208
#, no-c-format
msgid "Prevents the program from accessing the specified directory path entries. &aa; then continues to the next event."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1217
#, no-c-format
msgid "Prompts you to enter your own rule for this event, allowing you to specify a regular expression. If the expression does not actually satisfy the event that prompted the question in the first place, &aa; asks for confirmation and lets you reenter the expression."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1229
#, no-c-format
msgid "Select a specific path or create a general rule using wild cards that match a broader set of paths. To select any of the offered paths, enter the number that is printed in front of the path then decide how to proceed with the selected item."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1278
#, no-c-format
msgid "To view and edit your profile using <command>vi</command> , enter <command>vi /etc/apparmor.d/</command> <replaceable>PROFILENAME</replaceable> in a terminal window. To enable syntax highlighting when editing an &aa; profile in vim, use the commands <command>:syntax on</command> then <command>:set syntax=apparmor</command> . For more information about vim and syntax highlighting, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.apparmor.commandline.profiling.summary.vim\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: apparmor_profiles_man.xml:1290
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart &aa; and reload the profile set including the newly created one using the <command>systemctl reload apparmor</command> command."
